Projects

Beginning in September of 2021 I was placed onto a team of six developers to create an open source classroom polling software. This software would serve as a replacement for the currently running subscription-based service Learning Catalytics. Our project partner, Ethan Thatcher, is an active Physics professor at Oregon State University who wanted to provide students with the same experience as Learning Catalytics without having to pay over $70 on top of course enrollment.

Our six person team was split into a backend and frontend team with a member from each standing as a communications representative to coordinate with the project partner and other developing team. I was elected the communciations for the backend team given my prior experience with web-based databases and communcation skills. We decided to follow a scrum Agile framework which placed me as the scrum master of my developing team.

As a backend developer on this project I gained extensive experience working with Django's routing, admin, and API services. I found this experience reignited my passion for web-based development as the tools provided were so powerful. The main piece of the website's functionality I was put in charge of was user authentication and sessions. I applied Django's libraries and was able to get these functionalities implemented in a short period of time.

After nine months of development we were able to create a web application capable of providing users with the essential operations of a service like Learning Catalytics. This project was completed as a Senior Capstone Project for Oregon State University.

In December of 2021 I set out ot create a mobile application capable of telling users their Spotify Wrapped information at any point in the year. This concept came to me after my Spotify Wrapped 2021 came out and I wondered how a service like that would be on demand. I decided to use Kotlin to create this application and developed the program using Android Studio. Likely the most valuable piece of this project came from experience working with Spotify's API. This API experience would prove useful in many futue projects most notably the Open Source Classroom Polling Software I completed during my Senior Capstone at Oregon State University.
